  "prompt": "Why do people get headaches, puffy eyes and red nose after crying?",
  "response": "When people cry, several physiological responses occur that lead to these symptoms:\n\n1. Headaches:\n- Emotional stress and tension can cause muscle tightening\n- Crying releases stress hormones that can trigger tension headaches\n- Dehydration from crying can contribute to headache development\n\n2. Puffy eyes:\n- Tears contain salt, which can cause fluid retention around the eyes\n- Emotional crying triggers inflammation and increased blood flow\n- Lacrimal glands produce more tears, causing swelling of surrounding tissues\n- Crying can cause small blood vessels to dilate, leading to puffiness\n\n3. Red nose:\n- Increased blood flow during emotional states\n- Frequent wiping or blowing of the nose during crying\n- Capillaries in the nose expand, causing redness\n- Emotional stress can cause blood vessels to become more visible\n\nThese symptoms are typically temporary and subside within a few hours after crying. Drinking water, applying cool compresses, and resting can help reduce these effects. The physical response is a normal part of the body's emotional processing and stress release mechanism.",
